<font color="#FF0000">BENIFITING SOCIETY THEN &amp; NOW</font><br>
<tt>Mon Oct 20 13:03:35 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
John;<br>
Your question, &quot;how can our society benefit from our experiences and commitment to each other that we exhibited in 'Nam?&quot;<br><br>
John, it already has, the children we have given life to, understand the value of committment, and we still have a wealth of information to share with others that have never understood but desire to understand, what went wrong and what we contributed then, what we can contribute today is written in the lives and accomplishment of all those who post here and share from their heart and thereby change each other and histroy.<br>
A fellow Marine I had not spoken to in over 30 years, wrote me a letter, when I was in the process of seeking out former Marines I had served with for a reunion. I believe I might have posted part of it once before, but he very elequantly put into words what I feel, and with new veterans posting now, I have decide to post the complete letter, Ward Keeton was a machine gunner assigned to 1st platoon. He was wounded on November 19, 1967 during operation Foster. Enjoy, Cook.<br><br>
Dear cookie:<br><br>
To say that I was surprised when you called three weeks ago would be an understatement. Twenty-nine years ago on this date I was in the hospital at Cameron Bay after being wounded on Operation Foster. You were in the mist of a battle at Phu Binh 1 trying to survive the day. When I was medevacked on November 19th I remember looking down at the battlefield from the helicopter watching tracer rounds illuminate the twilight and wondered what would become of all the Marines in India Company. I was very pleased to learn from you that most did survive and went on to lead productive lives. After I left, my memories laid mostly dormant for many years. Occasionally I would over hear a conversation that would cause me to think back and once in awhile I would have a fleeting thought of places and people that I served with, but mostly went on with my life. Like you, I hardly ever talked with anyone about Viet Nam to any degree because most did not understand the intensity of our feelings and could not fathom the underlying emotion that we all had. I certainly never expected to contact anyone from India Company but was pleased when you called and totally overcome with the memories and the pride that we all feel. It is reinforcing to know that all you guys still remember. After all these years, we may not recall the places and events the same, but we do remember, and that is important. Looking at the photos that I have left, I see a bunch of kids, much like my own, who were not sure of what would become of them or why they did the things we did. But at the end of the day we had the certainty of each other and I believe we did quite well given the circumstances. If I had to do it over again I would want the same group of Marines at my side. Many in our country questioned and de-based our actions and the war that we fought but could not comprehend that freedom and liberty is non-selective, and resides only in those who fight for it, and then cherish it. The society that I see today is consumed with self-preference, greed and the desire to serve only the self. But buried in this society are the seeds of success for future generations, that being the children of all the servicemen who fought and died in Viet Nam and all other wars. These children have the traits of their fathers, passed on by us, and will certainly bloom and change our country. If it ever becomes necessary to protect our country in the ultimate battle, I feel confident that a group of Marines that I know personally, although gray and older, will move to the front, reassure the unknowing, space ourselves properly and move out!<br>
After I left the Marine Corps I worked with my dad in the construction field for a few years until changing careers in 1977. I used my VA benefits to acquire my advanced airmen certificates and have been flying professionally for eighteen years. My company manages a fleet of private business jets and we transport various business leaders to Canada, Mexico, Central and South America as well as the United States. It has been a very fulfilling career and I probably will continue for fifteen more years. I married my wife Jill on May 27, 1971 and we have two grown sons, Brad and Daniel. They both still live at home, one works and the other is a freshman in college. I am very proud of both. I was pleased to learn of your success in the criminal justice field and honor you for your service to God for the benefit of others. Like you, my life changed after Viet Nam. I have a deep respect for all living things and enjoy the little things in life.  Bass fishing, my Labrador retriever and all the small things remind me just how fortunate I am. I may not be a minister like you, but I do believe that I am here today because of the protective hand of God. My wife and I will probably retire in a few years and live at Lake Fork, just east of Dallas and my favorite place to be. Maybe by then we will have some grandchildren to tell stories to. With five daughters, it sounds like you will be busy for years to come!<br>
As to your questions concerning battle events, places and other Marines we served with, I will take a little time to recall as best I can then write it down in some kind of order and send it to you. Some of my memories are very vivid, some dim but I hope they will be helpful to you. I should be finished in about a week. Writing a book is an enormous task and I await the publication with enthusiasm. It speaks well of you to chronicle our lives as they were and have the patience to tackle this project. Again, thanks for calling me. Now I know that my memories and experiences of Viet Nam are also yours and all the other Marines from our Company and we can share them together. Enclosed are some of the photos that I have left including a handsome young man named “Cookie”! I hope they help you. If I’m not out of the country, I will try to attend the next reunion. Till then, watch your backside and keep your helmet on!<br><br>

<p><code>-- cookbarela@iname.com  (Cook Barela, Sparrowhawk) </code><p>


